Calidris alba, commonly known as the Sanderling, is a small wading bird of the family Scolopacidae.
It has a slim, compact body, short stout bill, and dark legs.
The Sanderling is known for its striking white plumage during the breeding season, which fades to grayish-brown in the non-breeding season.
It has a distinctive pattern of black feathers on its back, wings, and tail.
Sanderlings can be found on sandy beaches and tidal flats across the world, often searching for small crustaceans and insects in the sand.
They are migratory birds, breeding in the Arctic tundra and wintering along coastlines and beaches.
Sanderlings are important indicators of coastal ecosystem health and are studied by scientists to monitor changes in tidal environments.
